EIS is shown in Fig. 7g-h, and the charge storage performance of supercapacitors can be further evaluated using the equivalent series resistance (R

                           s
                        ) and charge transfer resistance (R

                           ct
                        ) [43–45]. Nyquist plots are fitted by the circuit model, as inserted in Fig. 7g. In the model, series of resistors are used to model different electrochemical reactions at MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC electrode. The intercept of the Nyquist curve at the real axis at higher frequency region, a semicircle at a moderate frequency region and a diagonal line at lower frequency region attribute to the solution resistance (Rs
                        ), charge transfer resistance (Rct
                        ) and Warburg resistance (Rw
                        ), respectively. It found that MoS2/CC has the lowest slope in the low-frequency region, indicating that its ion diffusion rate is slowest. However, when the HCNT and N-GQDs materials are introduced into the MoS2/CC electrode, MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC materials have the smallest R

                           s
                         (2.9 Ω) and R

                           ct
                         (0.95 Ω) (Fig. 7g), which is due to that HCNT provides the role of conductive channel for MoS2, while N-GQDs improve the wettability of the material and facilitate charge transfer between the electrode material and the electrolyte. Fig. 7h shows Nyquist plots of MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC with different rate of HCNT and N-GQDs (1: 1, 1: 2 and 1: 3) for exploring the influence of the ratio of carbon-based materials in the composite material. The Rs
                         is 2.7, 3.4, and 3.5 Ω with the increase of N-GQDs. The diameter of the semicircle represents the Rct
                        , which is related to the resistance of the current collector, electrode material and electrode/electrolyte interface. Obviously, the value of the Rct (0.95 Ω) was the smallest when the rate of HCNT and N-GQDs is 1: 1 in MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC, suggesting this ratio has the best conductivity and redox kinetics [46–48]. Furthermore, the cyclic stability of MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC at 30 mA cm−2 is shown in Fig. 7i. The capacitance retention of 89.2% was kept after 2500 cycles, indicating good cyclic stability. The influence of long cycle on the microscopic morphology of electrode materials was studied by the SEM images and XRD pattern. Fig. S1 (Supporting Information) shows the morphology of the MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC material after 2500 cycles. The surface morphology of the electrode material has no change significantly. The layered structure of MoS2 is still well maintained. The stability of the microstructure ensures the cycle stability of the electrode material. The XRD pattern of the MoS2/HCNT/N-GQDs@CC material after 2500 cycles (Fig. S2, Supporting Information) shows characteristic peaks of MoS2 at 14.33, 33.41, and 58.58°, indicating a better crystallinity. The characteristic peaks of N-GQDs at 24 and 43° and HCNT at 26.6° are still obvious, indicating that the carbon material does not fall off significantly.
